I can definitely sympathise of course with the people who are frustrated at people trying to transform D&D into a universal game. Mostly because it isn't, and trying to make it into that erodes the identity of D&D, and also robs you of the chance to play other games.

The idea that you would explore dangerous locations and grapple with traps and puzzles and riddles was also there from the start. As was the idea that you would interact with a cast of neutral or friendly NPCs in the local region. See Village of Hommlet or Keep on the Borderlands

Dungeons & Dragons is indeed combat heavy. This is because it's strongly inspired by action-heavy pulp fantasy of the mighty-thewed barbarian or sickly wizard-king wielding a cursed sword variety. But to say that it's a full 90% combat is pretty fuckin' disingenuous.

I'm beyond sick of the latest D&Discourse.

'D&D emphasises combat' and 'D&D can also do other things' are statements that can coexist, actually. 

Also 'it's fine to play D&D' and 'you should probably not use D&D for *everything*' are other statements that can coexist.

@erikscottdebie @SysDoesMatter @alien_dave @WinningerR @Wizards_DnD @DungeonScrawl Even the hyper-combat-focused 4e was pretty simple to run when you kept your powers written down and pre-calculated somewhere. And I hated 4e.

@lorenziniforce @rdonoghue The original d20 Modern was quite different, and much simpler; it was basically Dungeons & Dragons set in the modern day, with six base classes. Each one based around a core ability score. You then had advanced classes like, say, gunslinger or soldier or mage or other such.

@lorenziniforce @rdonoghue It also ditched hit points, any dice other than the d20 itself, classes, levels, races, and the magic systems.

It's basically my favourite d20 game, often even outdoing Dungeons & Dragons. But it is best at running its own identity, and that's comic-book superheroes.

@lorenziniforce @rdonoghue Literally the only time that the d20 system was able to produce something even remotely 'universal-esque' and it didn't fall flat on its face was Mutants & Masterminds. @lorenziniforce @rdonoghue Oh yeah. Dungeons & Dragons is absolutely great at being sword-and-sorcery but don't run it for a social intrigue game unless that social intrigue, like, takes place in Waterdeep or the Free City of Greyhawk or Absalom or something.

@alien_dave @erikscottdebie @WinningerR @Wizards_DnD @DungeonScrawl I haven't been playing the current edition for fourteen years and I'm not about to start now.

@erikscottdebie @alien_dave @WinningerR @Wizards_DnD @DungeonScrawl My biggest problems with 4e mechanically mostly revolved around how slow combat got at higher levels. The damage output did not keep up with monster hit points, so combat wound up taking longer and longer and was eventually a slog.

@erikscottdebie @alien_dave @WinningerR @Wizards_DnD @DungeonScrawl I remember that the AD&D 2e Dungeon Master Guide told you outright to award more experience for a difficult social encounter than for a battle where the fighter just picks off a bunch of low-level mooks. Or even to not reward experience at all for the latter.

@erikscottdebie @alien_dave @WinningerR @Wizards_DnD @DungeonScrawl As much attention is given over to traps and exploration, or for city interaction. Back in the 2e days they used to have reaction rolls where a given monster or non-player encounter might not necessarily react violently towards you if you're charismatic enough.
@erikscottdebie @alien_dave @WinningerR @Wizards_DnD @DungeonScrawl The terms for non-weapon proficiencies or skills or proficiencies or what have you change every other edition, I swear.

@erikscottdebie @alien_dave @WinningerR @Wizards_DnD @DungeonScrawl But you don't really need as many rules to run the non-combat elements of the game. @erikscottdebie @alien_dave @WinningerR @Wizards_DnD @DungeonScrawl In particular it owes a lot to the sword and sorcery action fantasy of Howard and Leiber and Moorcock, which was all about feats of derring-do and battling miscreants and monsters alike. It's not exactly a shock then that Dungeons & Dragons replicates that.

@spmcdonnell @Palitato @AlexandraErin There are also games that let you start with a higher baseline of proficiency, like Mutants & Masterminds or such, but very few of them really let you bypass the need to roll to attack entirely.

@Palitato @spmcdonnell @AlexandraErin Archery-obsessed yes, but at first level your character's just starting out and hasn't reached their actual peak yet. Dungeons & Dragons is about going from a nobody who can just about wave a sword or shoot a bow and becoming the great hero as you go along.

@spmcdonnell @Palitato @AlexandraErin And the seventy-year old elf won't necessarily have spent their whole life training archery. Instead they'll likely have spent their time engaging in idle pastimes, and learning the other bonus proficiencies and skills that elves gain for free.
